🔹 What is ThreadLocal in Java?

ThreadLocal is a class in Java that provides thread-specific variables.

👉 It means each thread has its own separate copy of a variable.
Even if multiple threads access the same ThreadLocal object, they cannot see each other’s values.

🔹 Why Do We Need ThreadLocal?

Normally, instance variables are shared between threads, which may cause:

Race conditions

Data inconsistency

Synchronization issues

But ThreadLocal solves this by giving:

✅ Independent variable per thread

🔹 Real-Life Example

Imagine:

3 users are using an e-commerce application.

Each user request is handled by a different thread.

You want to store userId for the current request.

If you use a normal variable → It may get overridden by another thread.

If you use ThreadLocal → Each thread stores its own userId.

🔹 Simple Example in Java
class ThreadLocalExample {

    private static ThreadLocal<String> threadLocal = new ThreadLocal<>();

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Runnable task = () -> {
            threadLocal.set(Thread.currentThread().getName());
            System.out.println("Value: " + threadLocal.get());
        };

        Thread t1 = new Thread(task);
        Thread t2 = new Thread(task);

        t1.start();
        t2.start();
    }
}
🔹 Output (Example)
Value: Thread-0
Value: Thread-1

package com.practics.threadPractics;

public class ThreadLocalExample {
    /**
     * here the threadlocal will create seperate variable for each thread.
     */
    private final static ThreadLocal<Long> threadLocal=new ThreadLocal<>();
    public static void main(String[] args) {

         long userId=1234L;
         long userId2=6543L;

        new Thread(()->{
          try{
              threadLocal.set(userId);
              System.out.println("Value : "+ threadLocal.get());
          }catch (Exception e){
              System.out.println(e.getMessage());
          }finally {
              threadLocal.remove();
//              System.out.println("value removed : "+threadLocal.get());
          }
        }).start();

        new Thread(()->{
