ThreadLocal is a Java class that allows us to create thread-specific variables where each thread has its own independent 
copy of the variable, preventing shared data conflicts.


🔹 What is InheritableThreadLocal?

InheritableThreadLocal is a subclass of ThreadLocal.

👉 It allows a child thread to inherit the value of the parent thread.

🔹 Normal ThreadLocal Behavior

With normal ThreadLocal:

Parent thread sets value

Child thread CANNOT see it

Example:

ThreadLocal<String> tl = new ThreadLocal<>();

tl.set("ParentValue");

new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println(tl.get()); // null
}).start();

Child gets null.

🔹 InheritableThreadLocal Behavior

With InheritableThreadLocal:

Parent sets value

Child thread automatically gets a copy of that value

Example:

InheritableThreadLocal<String> itl = new InheritableThreadLocal<>();

itl.set("ParentValue");

new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println(itl.get()); // ParentValue
}).start();

✔ Child inherits parent’s value.

🔥 How It Works Internally

Every Thread in Java has:

ThreadLocalMap → for ThreadLocal

inheritableThreadLocals → for InheritableThreadLocal

When a child thread is created:

JVM copies parent's inheritable values into child.

🔹 Important Interview Question

If parent changes value after child creation, will child see updated value?

❌ No.

Because child gets a copy at the time of thread creation, not a live reference.

🔹 Real Example With Both
public class InheritableExample {

    private static InheritableThreadLocal<String> itl =
            new InheritableThreadLocal<>();

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        itl.set("Parent Thread Value");

        Thread child = new Thread(() -> {
            System.out.println("Child Value: " + itl.get());
        });

        child.start();
    }
}

Output:

Child Value: Parent Thread Value
🔴 Very Important Warning (For Spring Boot Developers Like You)

InheritableThreadLocal does NOT work properly with ThreadPool.

Why?

Because:

Thread pools reuse threads.

Threads are not newly created.

So inheritance does not happen.

That’s why frameworks like Spring Security do not rely only on InheritableThreadLocal in thread pools.
